@page "/help"
@attribute [ExcludeFromInteractiveRouting]

@using Anchor.Domain.Identity
@using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization

@attribute [Authorize(Policy = ApplicationPolicies.AdminAccess)]

<PageTitle>Help</PageTitle>

<section class="admin-page">
    <div class="page-hero page-hero--section">
        <p class="page-hero__eyebrow">Admin Help</p>
        <h1>Help</h1>
        <p class="page-hero__lead">
            This guide is available to Admin accounts and is organized by subject and role type so staff setup,
            editor ownership, and security responsibilities stay easy to review.
        </p>
    </div>

    <StatusMessage />

    <section class="admin-card">
        <div class="admin-card__header">
            <h2>Browse by subject</h2>
            <span class="admin-card__badge">Admin reference</span>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Subject</p>
                <h3>Staff onboarding</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Admins create staff accounts, then assign roles.</li>
                    <li>An <strong>Admin</strong> creates each staff account and shares the temporary password with that employee directly.</li>
                    <li>The site uses local sign-in and optional passkeys only. External provider sign-in is not part of this setup.</li>
                    <li>After the account exists, an <strong>Admin</strong> assigns only the operational or technical roles that person actually needs.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Subject</p>
                <h3>Passwords and profile upkeep</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>If a staff member forgets the current password, an <strong>Admin</strong> can set a fresh temporary password from <strong>User Management</strong>.</li>
                    <li><strong>User Management</strong> keeps each employee's first name, last name, and phone number current.</li>
                    <li><strong>Manage Account</strong> lets each signed-in user update the same first name, last name, and phone number details for their own account.</li>
                    <li>When an <strong>Admin</strong> changes someone else's role or sign-in approval, that staff member only needs to refresh the page to pick up the new access.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Subject</p>
                <h3>Account approval and security</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>If confirmed-account enforcement is enabled, an <strong>Admin</strong> can confirm or unconfirm sign-in access from <strong>User Management</strong> without changing email verification.</li>
                    <li>The fallback confirmed-account value lives in <code>appsettings.json</code>, and an environment variable can still override the live behavior.</li>
                    <li><strong>Security</strong> shows both the effective value and the fallback file value.</li>
                    <li>Do not remove the final <strong>Admin</strong> or final <strong>IT</strong> assignment, and do not remove <strong>Admin</strong> from your own signed-in account.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Subject</p>
                <h3>Menu publishing workflow</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li><strong>Menu Editor</strong> manages four fixed public tabs: <strong>Breakfast</strong>, <strong>Lunch</strong>, <strong>Dinner</strong>, and <strong>Drinks</strong>.</li>
                    <li>Staff switch between dedicated <strong>Food</strong>, <strong>Drinks</strong>, and <strong>Hours</strong> workspaces instead of working through one long stacked form.</li>
                    <li>The Food and Drinks workspaces use a section tree on the left and one explicit-save detail panel on the right so staff can stay focused on a single record at a time.</li>
                    <li>Specials are now first-class menu items with an attached special schedule block. Staff edit the shared item fields once, then turn on <strong>Is special</strong> when the item needs weekday or dated special behavior.</li>
                    <li>The browser tree supports both meal filtering and content filtering so staff can focus on <strong>Standard</strong> items, <strong>Specials</strong>, or the full mixed catalog.</li>
                    <li>The browser tree supports <strong>Active</strong>, <strong>Both</strong>, and <strong>Archived</strong> views. Archived records appear muted, while hidden records stay visible with their own status treatment.</li>
                    <li>Section and item ordering use the same live tree controls: <strong>Up</strong> and <strong>Down</strong> move one slot at a time, while drag-and-drop drops the record directly into its new slot.</li>
                    <li>Menu-hour inputs accept shorthand such as <strong>1300</strong> or <strong>1pm</strong> and also provide a reusable time-pick list so staff do not have to memorize one rigid format. Save stays disabled until every available day has valid opening and closing times.</li>
                    <li>The public menu now groups repeated hours into compact ranges such as <strong>Daily</strong>, <strong>Monday-Friday</strong>, or <strong>Sunday-Thursday</strong>, while still keeping today's hours visible at a glance.</li>
                    <li>The public menu now uses a left sidebar for <strong>Breakfast</strong>, <strong>Lunch</strong>, <strong>Dinner</strong>, and <strong>Drinks</strong>, with each service showing its serving hours directly under the navigation link.</li>
                    <li>Public menu categories open as accordion sections so guests can focus on one category at a time, with the first visible category expanded by default.</li>
                    <li>On larger screens, the public menu and Menu Editor expand to use the available browser width so staff can review more sections and form fields without feeling boxed into a narrow center column.</li>
                    <li>Use <strong>Archive</strong> when an item or section should disappear from the guest view without being permanently deleted. Special items archive the same way as standard items. <strong>Delete</strong> always requires a second confirmation.</li>
                    <li>Public menu labels such as <strong>Coming Soon</strong>, <strong>Seasonal</strong>, and <strong>Limited Time</strong> are derived from menu offer dates at runtime.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Subject</p>
                <h3>Bootstrap safety</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>The app seeds required roles automatically on startup.</li>
                    <li>The bootstrap user stops seeding once the system has at least one <strong>Admin</strong> and one <strong>IT</strong> user.</li>
                    <li>The seeded password must be changed before that account can open the rest of the site.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="admin-card">
        <div class="admin-card__header">
            <h2>Browse by role type</h2>
            <span class="admin-card__badge">Responsibility map</span>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Role Type</p>
                <h3>Admin</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Own <strong>User Management</strong>, <strong>Security</strong>, <strong>Publicity Editor</strong>, and <strong>Contact Editor</strong>.</li>
                    <li>Help is available to Admin accounts so onboarding, role assignment, and security rules stay easy to review.</li>
                    <li>Admins do not use <strong>Event Editor</strong> or <strong>Menu Editor</strong> unless those roles are assigned separately in a future change.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Role Type</p>
                <h3>EventManager</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Use <strong>Event Editor</strong> to add, update, and remove event listings.</li>
                    <li>This role does not automatically grant menu, publicity, contact, security, or user-management access.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Role Type</p>
                <h3>MenuManager</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Use <strong>Menu Editor</strong> to maintain sections, price variants, menu items, optional item descriptions, special-item schedule extensions, and per-tab service hours.</li>
                    <li>Item save errors appear inside the detail panel near the action buttons, so staff do not need to scroll back to the top of the page to see why a save failed.</li>
                    <li>Text-entry fields across the Menu Editor and other admin forms accept both normal typing and committed text input, so Windows voice dictation and similar accessibility tools work more consistently.</li>
                    <li>Food items can appear on Breakfast, Lunch, and Dinner. Drink items belong to the Drinks tab through their section family.</li>
                    <li>Hide a menu item when it should appear only through a special offer instead of the regular public catalog.</li>
                    <li>The shared time-picker input keeps opening and closing hours visually consistent across future editors anywhere staff need to select a time.</li>
                    <li>This role does not automatically grant event, publicity, contact, security, or user-management access.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="feature-card feature-card--tight">
                <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Role Type</p>
                <h3>IT</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Use <strong>IT / System</strong> for technical and future diagnostic work.</li>
                    <li>The <strong>IT</strong> role still does not grant Admin-only security or user-management access by itself.</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</section>
